	       		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/69c75e559d4fc324e9e3b0ad8b6896c0?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<p>My submissive partner enjoys denial; I do not. Ergo, we don&#8217;t do a lot of it when we&#8217;re together &#8211; when we&#8217;re geographically apart, we can do it as it doesn&#8217;t directly affect me. This would, if denial made him submissive, mean that he is more submissive at certain times, which is not my experience. </p>
<p>The discourse of male submission as requiring or even being created by denial also phrases submission which does not involve denial as not genuine or less submissive. I do not hold with that.</p>
